derstandings of race and racism within the United States and Mexico. Within their communities and networks that span an international border, Zamora argues, immigrants come to define "race" in a way distinct from both the color-conscious hierarchy of Mexican society and the Black-White binary prevalent within the United States. In the process, their stories demonstrate how race is not static, but rather an evolving social phenomenon forever altered by immigration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMexicansxRace identityzUnited States. 0aMexicanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRacismzMexico. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aLatino.  aMexican migration.  aMexico.  aimmigration.  amestizaje.  arace and ethnicity.  arace relations.  aracial hierarchy.  aracialization.  atransnationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363225740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632257/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles